\textbf{Question}:\\
For what values of x, the numbers $-\frac{2}{7}\,,x,-\frac{7}{2}\,$ are in G.P ?
\\\\
\textbf{Solution: }\\
Let $a,b,c$ be any three consecutive terms of a GP whose common difference is $r$ then,
\begin{align}
\implies\frac{b}{a}\,&=\frac{c}{b}\,=r
\\\implies \frac{x}{(-\frac{2}{7}\,)}\,&= \frac{(-\frac{7}{2}\,)}{x}\, \\
x^2&=(-\frac{2}{7}\,)\cdot(-\frac{7}{2}\,)\\
x^2&=1\\
x&=1,-1\\
r&=\frac{x}{(-\frac{2}{7}\,)}\\
\implies r&=\frac{7}{2}\,or -\frac{7}{2}\,\\
T_n&=-\frac{2}{7}\,\cdot(-\frac{7}{2}\,)^{n}  \text{ or } -\frac{2}{7}\,\cdot(\frac{7}{2}\,)^{n}\\
T_n&=(-\frac{7}{2}\,)^{n-1}  \text{ or } -(\frac{7}{2}\,)^{n-1} 
\end{align}
The signal corresponding to this is 
\begin{align}
x(n)&=(-\frac{7}{2}\,)^{n-1}\,u(n)\,  \text{ or } -(\frac{7}{2}\,)^{n-1}\,u(n)
\end{align}
\begin{figure}[h]
    \renewcommand\thefigure{1}
    \centering
    \captionsetup{justification=centering}
    \includegraphics[width=1.1\linewidth]{/home/dilip/Desktop/EE1205/assignment_11_9_3_6/figs/graph1.png}
